===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|bannen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|bannan||to summon, command, proclaim, call out|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|bannanan|curse, forbid}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|bʰa-|to say|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|bannen||to ban, exile, discard|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|bannen||to exorcise, captivate, excommunicate|lang=de}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|banna||to ban, scold|lang=sv}}, Armenian {{term|բան|tr=ban|lang=hy}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|bans|banning|banned|banned}}

# {{transitive|obsolete}} To [[summon]]; [[call out]].
# {{transitive}} To [[anathematise]]; [[pronounce]] an ecclesiastical [[curse]] upon; place under a ban.
# {{transitive}} To [[curse]]; [[execrate]].
# {{transitive}} To [[prohibit]]; [[interdict]]; [[proscribe]]; [[forbid]] or block from participation.
#: ''Bare feet are '''banned''' in this establishment''.
# {{intransitive}} To curse; [[utter]] curses or maledictions.

